/     %h1 Winemakers
/     %p Because of marketing deadlines, many winemakers have to write out their tasting notes before the wines are out of their barrels. That's like trying to predict what musical instrument your daughter is going to play while she's still in the womb. If you're a real-deal winemaker, Bloocher is an effective tool to differentiate your work. The more details you tell about your wine's story &mdash; where you sourced your fruit, your wine log, which type of oak chips you used, how much tartaric acid you added, and which species of fish bladder you used for clarification &mdash; the more authentic your story will be. So own those details, even if you think they might scare off the weese. And while it's possible that another winemaker will look at your story and try to steal your secret sauce, it's much more likely that you'll gain the respect of someone who wants to learn. 

